##To combat the new crown, Ridgeville entered Phase III clinical trials

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

The drug, called Remdesivir, also received unprecedented attention overnight. Can this drug really change the current situation of incurable new coronavirus infection?

By Yan Yan

"wonder drug" for newly diagnosed patients in the United States

On Jan. 19, a 35 year old man was admitted to an emergency medical clinic in Washington state. The next day, he was diagnosed with America's first new coronavirus pneumonia. According to him, he briefly returned to Wuhan a few days ago to visit his family and returned to the United States on January 15. He had coughed for four days before going to the hospital and also had symptoms of fever. Concerned about a health alert from the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention about a new Chinese coronavirus, he decided to go to the hospital to be sure. However, not only did he not spend time in the south China Seafood Market, nor did he have any contact with any patients during his time in Wuhan.

His nasopharyngeal and Oropharyngeal swabs tested positive for 2019-nCoV and he was subsequently admitted to an isolation ward at a local medical centre.

During this period, the hospital adopted a more conservative treatment. It wasn't until the fifth night (Day 9) that doctors noticed signs of pneumonia in the lower left lobe of his chest, oxygen Saturation, measured by an oximeter, drops to 90% (in healthy people, 94% to 100% Oxygenation) . Soon, on the sixth day, his condition began to deteriorate. He began to need oxygen. The doctor's Auscultation also found Rales in his lungs. He began to have a fever. On the seventh day, with no progress in treatment and a marked deterioration in his condition, doctors injected him intravenously with an unmarketed drug, Remdesivir, and on the following day his blood oxygen levels rose to more than 94% , the doctor found that the Rales in his lungs had disappeared and his appetite had improved markedly. As of January 30, he was still hospitalized, but all of his symptoms had abated except for a cough.

On January 31, the The New England Journal of Medicine reported on the slow recovery of the country's first new coronavirus case.

It is worth noting that the clinical use of "Red Xiwei" is not on the market, is still in clinical research and development stage of the drug. It was originally developed for Zaire Ebolavirus by Gilead Sciences, and has now completed phase III trials.

The common question is: First of all, drug development usually takes a long time, whether the drug has not been developed, the epidemic has passed? Moreover, this is only a clinical trial in the United States, which, according to standard practice, will need to be redone if the drug is to be marketed in China. Second, since the drug is not on the market, this patient in the United States is through what kind of medicine?

The good news is that the application for a clinical trial of Radzivir has been accepted, according to the website of the State Food and Drug Administration. Starting Feb. 3, a randomized, double blind, placebo controlled Phase III clinical trial will be led by Professor Cao Bin of the China Japan Friendship Hospital, in which 270 patients with mild to moderate cases of new coronavirus pneumonia will be enrolled, the aim was to assess the safety and efficacy of the drug in inhibiting novel coronavirus infection.

"The cellular trial of the Drug Ridicivir for Zaire ebolavirus is effective and clinically safe, but data on clinical efficacy are not yet available. With the approval of the relevant State Administration and the review of the Ethics Committee, the urgent initiation of Phase III clinical practice in our country is acceptable to a certain extent,"said Li Taisheng, director of the Department of Infectious Diseases at the Peking Union Medical College Hospital, in a previous interview. You know, the CDE didn't reply to the Drug Company within 60 days of a clinical request for a new drug following established protocol.

This is also in line with the "special task" principle. "because of the direct correlation between antiviral drugs and the emergency, the new coronavirus outbreak has become a public health event and will not normally be approved in the usual way. And the progression of the disease is just a few days, very fast, and the effect is relatively easy to see clinically,"Wu told scidev.net. He is a former head of antiviral R & D for The Hoffmann-La Roche Group, which currently works on drugs related to human respiratory syncytial virus. There are more than a dozen natural viruses that can infect the human respiratory tract, including coronavirus, the subject of the outbreak. "Most anti-infective drugs do take less time in clinical trials, compared with the development of cancer drugs that people are concerned about. This is mainly because the drug targets the virus, the safety window is larger, faster in the clinical, and the anti-cancer drug targets the human protein, clinical design needs to consider more. The clinical trial is expected to end on April 27, "although it is expected to end in April, but if the drug works well, the trial will end ahead of schedule. ". Qian Jiahua, chief scientist of the National Drug Review Center, said in an earlier interview.

Pity the hope of the medicated?

As for why the American patient was able to Use an unmarketed drug, the reason was based on a mechanism called Compassionate Use. The system is a special policy introduced by the FDA in 2009 that allows doctors to apply for unmarketed drugs that are still under development in the event of an urgent, life threatening condition that is not treatable. The trigger conditions for this mechanism are also severe, such as when a patient's condition must be extremely critical and clinical trials in humans are not possible. The FDA's website also lists detailed approval figures: in 2017, only 1,000 patients were approved for compassionate use.

The existence of "sympathetic medication" mechanism is the hope of patients' survival. In 2017, the China Food and Drug Administration also issued a Chinese version of the sympathy letter, which gives regulators more flexibility in strictly regulating the approval of new drugs. Wu Zheng told the economist, "We were in a Phase II human respiratory syncytial virus clinic in Turkey, and we were able to use the empathy drug under the right conditions. Now that the clinical work of Professor Cao Bin at the China Japan Friendship Hospital has been synchronized, sympathetic treatment is not out of the question. In particular, the current outbreak is in line with the situation there is no cure, which is a drug that has done a lot of clinical trials. If the patient's life is in danger and there is no cure, it is ethical for the doctor to use the drug under study.".

We spoke to Shao Yu, who has spent years in basic virology, about why an Ebola drug might work in patients with the new coronavirus pneumonia. He mentioned that, "whether it's HIV, SARS or this COVID-19, they're all RNA viruses. During the life cycle of a virus, it depends on the RNA polymerase in the host cell to complete its own transcription or replication. That's one of the reasons that professor Wang said earlier that the HIV drug seemed to work for him, because it works the same way, so it can also work against SARS and COVID-19. The current clinical treatment is still based on the experience of SARS, the new crown and SARS is highly homologous, the same pathogenesis, based on Gilead's previous clinical practice, we also have reason to believe that the drug can have a certain effect on the new crown.

Shao Yu's explanation points to the "broad-spectrum mechanism" of antiviral drug, "In other words, in theory, the drug could inhibit RNA viruses that depend on the function of their host RNA polymerase. To make a less apt analogy, Th√©noz is a broad-spectrum antipyretic that, in addition to being used as an anti-flu agent, can also be used for many infections or non-infectious fevers."

But that's just how the drug works, and whether it works in patients, and whether it's a good fit for mass marketing, will have to wait for data from clinical trials.

The effects are still unknown, and the looting has begun

In this regard, Gilead's position is also very cautious, "there is no data on 2019-nCo, and the safety and efficacy of Radzivir have not been proven. In the case of the United States, Gilead offered Ridgeville to a small number of patients infected with the 2019-nCoV for emergency treatment, with the support of local regulators, upon request by the treating physician who weighed the risks against the benefits. We are also advancing the use of the 2019-nCoV virus sample for appropriate laboratory testing of Radzivir. Although there is currently no antiviral data to show the activity of redcoat against the 2019-nCoV, the availability of data against other coronaviruses gives us hope. In Vitro and animal models, Ridgeville has been shown to be active against both Atypical pneumonia and Mers viral pathogens, which are also coronaviruses and structurally very similar to the 2019-nCoV."

On the other hand, Wang Guangfa, director of Peking University First Hospital, whose symptoms had been greatly relieved by the use of Abbvie's anti-aids drug, "Lopinavitonavir" (cleats) , despite repeated reports, it's just his personal condition. We can't be sure it's working for other patients. However, the reality is still a large number of "suspected cases" through smuggling and other underground channels to buy and sell drugs, prescription medicine cleats even was once fired to a thousand yuan. This newspaper contacted two AIDS patients who were "required" to sell drugs, and they mentioned that, "Some people are particularly eloquent, saying that the fourth edition of the Medical Treatment Plan of the Health Commission emphasizes that before there is an effective antiviral drug, you can try the Kleenex, and I am willing to pay for it. Don't you sell it? " Li Taisheng, director of the Peking Union Medical College Hospital Department of Infectious Diseases, who was interviewed earlier by the media, stressed, one of the necessities of prescription is that the drug has side effects, which can lead to diarrhea, high blood sugar, and abnormal liver function.

Overall, clinical trials of the new coronavirus have already begun, and even if the new coronavirus pneumonia outbreak improves soon, current trials could help with potential future infections. "think of all the new drugs for coronaviruses that would have been developed without Radicivir. Commercialization of drugs may be difficult, but antiviral drug itself is broad-spectrum, and there may be other antiviral scenarios in the future." Wu Zheng told the economist.

You know, if Gilead had not developed Ridgeville for Ebola, we would now have one less candidate for a new coronavirus. With no one able to accurately predict how the epidemic will unfold, a "wonder drug" is more than a hope. It is a responsibility.
